b'' b'' b'#i use xwd/xpr (from the x11r5 dist.) and various programs of the' b'#ppm-tools to print hardcopies of colored x windows. my problem is,' b'' b"i don't like xpr. it gives (at least, the x11r4 version does) louzy" b'output: the hardcopy looks very grainy to me.' b'instead, i use pnmtops. this takes full advantage postscript, and' b'lets the printer do the dirty job of dithering a (graylevel)' b'image to black and white dots.' b'' b'so: if you have a postscript printer, try:' b'xwdtopnm <xwdfile |\t# convert to ppm' b'[ppmtopgm |]\t\t# to graylevel for smaller file to print' b'pnmtops -noturn |\t# to postscript' b'lpr\t\t\t# print' b'' b'pnmtops has several neat options, but use them with care:' b'if you want your image to be wide, use:' b'pnmtops -noturn -scale -width b'-noturn prevents the image from being rotated (if it is wider than it' b'is high)' b'-width specifies the paper width (not the image width see below)' b'-scale is used because if the image is small, it may fit within a' b'width less than and will thus be printed smaller than wide.' b'if you first scale it up a lot, it will certainly not fit in and' b'will be scaled down by pnmtops automatically to fit the specified' b'paper width.' b'in short: pnmtops will scale an image down to fit the paper size,' b'but it will not blow it up automatically.' b'' b'hope this helps.' b'marcel.' b'--' b'|x|\t faculty of mathematics and computer science' b'x\t university of amsterdam the netherlands' b"======life stinks. fortunately, i've got a cold.========" 